  "family": "Ritter Reaction",
  "candidate": {
    "substrate_smiles": [
      "CC(C)(C)O",
      "CC#N"
    ],
    "product_smiles": [
      "CC(=O)NC(C)(C)C"
    ],
    "optional_reagent_smiles": [
      "O=S(=O)(O)O"
    ],
    "rationale": "This reaction is a classic textbook example of the Ritter reaction. Tert-butanol is protonated by sulfuric acid and loses water to form the stable tert-butyl carbocation. This carbocation is then trapped by the nucleophilic nitrogen of acetonitrile, forming a nitrilium ion intermediate. Subsequent hydrolysis yields N-tert-butylacetamide. All reactants and products are simple, acyclic, and lack complex functional groups, making this a clear and unambiguous representation of the core transformation.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "This example uses simple, acyclic aliphatic substrates (tert-butanol and acetonitrile) to avoid overlap with other named reactions involving aromatic rings, complex ring systems, or other reactive functional groups. The formation of a simple secondary amide from a tertiary alcohol and a nitrile is highly characteristic of the Ritter reaction and unlikely to be confused with other transformations."
  }
}
